Tenant Fees & Charges

Mandatory charges associated with the setting up of your tenancy

There are various fees and charges associated with renting a property that you should be aware of when considering making an offer on a property. More detailed information is available upon request.

(Where not payable you will be advised accordingly)

Preliminary Charge - 42% Inc. VAT of the first months rent or £420 Inc. VAT, whichever is the greater.
This charge all inclusive charge covers the tenancy agreement, referencing and the check-in. It is not collected until the landlord has, subject-to-contact and references, accepted your offer. If the tenancy does not proceed for whatever reason we will refund a proportionate amount of the charge based on work undertaken and costs incurred.

Short Let Fee – From £440 (Inc. VAT)†

This charge applies to short term lettings only and covers: The cost of preparing an Agreement; an inventory check-in and an end of tenancy clean (excluding carpets).

Other funds you should allow for

Payment of Intent – To be agreed with you

We may require a payment of intent as confirmation of your intent to proceed with the proposed tenancy. This will be put towards your first rental payment and will only be refunded if our client elects not to proceed. Payment of this sum does not constitute the granting of a tenancy.

Rent in Advance – 1 Month

You will usually be required to pay 1 months rent in advance.

Deposit – Equivalent to 6 weeks rent

The deposit is held to protect your landlord from you not meeting your obligations under the terms of the tenancy.

Stamp Duty Land Tax

This tax is payable on tenancies where the rent exceeds £125,000.

Charges if you terminate your tenancy Change of Sharer - £420 Inc. VAT

This charge applies when you wish to replace a named tenant with another tenant part way through your tenancy and your landlord has agreed to the change. Please note that the replacement tenant will be charged separately for referencing in the sum of £54 Inc. VAT each.

Deed of Surrender - £75 Inc. VAT

This charge applies to preparation of documentation where, at your request, the landlord has agreed to release you from the tenancy early.

Charges if you renew your tenancy

Memorandum of Renewal - £90 Inc. VAT

This charge covers the cost of preparing a basic document to confirm details of any renewal.

Renewal Tenancy Agreement - £150 Inc. VAT

This charge covers the cost of preparing a more extensive renewal document where changes to the terms agreed dictate.

Potential charges at the end of your tenancy

Future Landlord Reference - £30 Inc. VAT

This charge applies when you ask us to provide a reference to a future landlord.

† Based on a 2 bedroom property in London.
listing.description: A delightful detached Grade II listed family house with a unique and versatile layout which has been refurbished and modernised in many areas whilst retaining some fine period features such as exposed beams and fireplaces. Offered in good order throughout and with no onward chain, points of particular note include the following: A well fitted and equipped kitchen/breakfast room with outlooks of the garden and beyond, a range of wall and base units, a larder cupboard, long work surfaces, an oil fired aga which also provides hot water and ample space for a table and chairs. An adjacent dining room with large Jerusalem stone tiled flooring and opens into a delightful wooden constructed conservatory with windows all around and French doors opening onto the garden and a glimpse of Bewl Water. An elegant sitting room with exposed beams and a large inglenook fireplace with wood burning stove which leads into a snug/family room with wooden flooring and feature fireplace with marble surround. To the first floor there are four bedrooms. The principal bedroom has a feature brick surround fireplace and a well fitted en suite shower room and all bedrooms enjoy lovely rural outlooks. The guest bedroom has fantastic views of the garden and surround. To the top floor is a further bedroom which has an en suite shower room and a range of fitted cupboards.SituationThe house sits on elevated ground within the High Weald; an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty and on the eastern edge of Bewl Water reservoir – the largest inland area of water in the South East. The picturesque villages of Ticehurst, Lamberhurst and Wadhurst are about 2 miles, 3.5 miles and 5 miles respectively for local shopping and the popular spa town of Tunbridge Wells lies about 10 miles to the north-west for more comprehensive shopping. The area is very well served for schools for both boys and girls of all ages and there is superb outriding all around the reservoir and at nearby Bedgebury Forest.OutsideThe property is approached via a 5 bar wooden gate onto a gravel driveway which provides parking and a garage with additional storage adjacent and above. The garden is well established and mainly laid to lawn. In all about 0.6 acres.Additional InformationTrain Services: Wadhurst Station, about 6.5 miles, Frant Station, about 9 miles and Tonbridge Station, about 17 miles all offering fast trains to London. Road Connections: The location is superb for the A21 and M25 motorway. Nearby Golf Clubs: Dale Hill and Lamberhurst.

listing.description: Elegant Four Bedroom Period Classic With Bright Tasteful FinishThis fine four bedroom Victorian gem is definitely one to view! The living accommodation is spread over three floors and you have a large corner plot including a sunny rear and side garden with side access. The interior is tastefully presented, conducive to modern living with two smart bathrooms, a contemporary kitchen adjoining the bright living space and four double bedrooms. The current owners have secured planning permission for a double storey side return and rear extension. If you're looking for a project to sink your teeth into, we have the architect plans available.Entering on the raised ground floor you'll be pleased to find original dado rails separating complimentary wall shades. Rich hardwood flooring runs from the hall into the bright rear facing well stocked kitchen. Here you'll fall in love with thick solid counters, sleek white cabinets, a one and a half bowl sink and drainer and a cracking five ring gas range. There's a pretty garden view through a wooden framed sash over the sink. The reception adjoins the kitchen, where a slightly arched front facing sash boasts stripped wooden shutters.The lower return hosts a handy utility and wc which is light and lovely owing to its triple aspect. To the rear, a south–facing patio area and lush healthy lawn make for the perfect bbq venue. Back inside, moving downstairs finds you inspecting the first two double bedrooms. The larger bedroom benefits from fitted shelving units. There's another bathroom on this level and plenty of storage under the stairs. Up to the first return you'll discover a nicely presented bathroom with Travertine floor, wall and counter tiling, bath and shower and vintage radiator. The first floor hosts two more light and airy double bedrooms - the main bedroom with twin sash windows overlooking the front garden, has handy fitted wardrobes. The property also benefits from ample storage, with a loft, cellar and garden shed. Parking is easy as the road is in an unrestricted parking zone.Well located for Rye Lane, Camberwell Green and Kings College Hospital, the house is less than a 10-minute walk to Peckham Rye station (zone 2) for Victoria, London Bridge and Blackfriars. Peckham Rye also has the London Overground Line, with great connections to Clapham Junction, Canada Water and trendy East London. Several buses run into town along the nearby Peckham Road, with just a 15 minute ride to Elephant & Castle or Oval tube stations. Bellenden Road, with delis, cafés and award-winning butcher, is a quick stroll through Warwick Gardens. Also within walking distance are numerous local highlights: Alsop and Stormer’s Peckham library, the contemporary South London Gallery and a Sunday Farmers Market on Camberwell Green, which has recently reopened after a £13m refurbishment.

Transparency for tenants

Once you've found the perfect property and your offer has been accepted, we'll start preparing the tenancy agreement and organising the logistics for your 'move-in' day. The tenancy charges may vary, depending on the agreement we have with the landlord, so it's best to ask the Marsh & Parsons office dealing with your offer for a full break down of costs.

That said, we don't want you to have any unwelcome surprises when it comes to signing the contract, so here's a list of what you can typically expect to pay:

Pre-Tenancy All Fees stated are inclusive of VAT (calculated at 20%)

Tenancy Agreement / Admin Fee £270
Referencing Fee £30 per reference (including references for any proposed Guarantor)
Check-in Fee £130.80
Deposit Typically six weeks rent
Pet Deposit Returnable additional security deposit, equivalent to two weeks' rent

During your tenancy (if required) All Fees stated are inclusive of VAT (calculated at 20%)
Renewal Document Fee £72
Change of Occupancy £120
Future Landlord Reference Fee £36

For more information regarding the lettings process, please visit the Lettings Advice for Tenants page.


Fees explained


Tenancy Agreement/Admin Fee - Provision of an expertly written tenancy agreement, brokering agreed amendments between landlord and tenant, and arrangement for completion and signature of the agreement by both parties, and registering your deposit with the Tenancy Deposit Scheme. Your deposit is typically six weeks rent.

Referencing Fee - The cost of referencing includes checking your credit status, previous employer, current or past landlords, and taking into account any other information to help assess the affordability of your tenancy application.

Check-in Fee - The cost of arranging for a clerk to meet you and agree the current inventory of the property at the start of your tenancy. The cost of the check-out at the end of the tenancy is met by the landlord.

Pet Deposit (Returnable) - To cover the added risk of property damage. This will be protected with your security deposit and may be returned at the end of the tenancy.

Renewal Document Fee - Contract negotiation, amending and updating terms and arranging a further tenancy and agreement.

Change of Occupancy - Contract negotiation, amending and updating terms and arranging a further tenancy and agreement.

Future Landlord Reference Fee - Collating information and preparing a reference for a future landlord or letting agent.

listing.description: The exclusive and much envied Shrewsbury Wood development lies within the heart of Prestwich Clough, which, whilst being a tranquil conservation area with protected wildlife, is itself approximately four miles from Manchester City Centre and only a mile away from the vibrant, bustling and thriving Prestwich Village with its quality schools, renowned restaurants, shops and bars.Built to the highest of specifications and designed by someone with a clear eye for detail, Cardwells are privileged to be chosen by Danat Homes, as the exclusive agent to market these exquisite and architecturally stunning six bedroom, six bathroom detached family homes. Set within landscaped gardens, each of these Freehold properties has a double garage plus private parking for up to six vehicles -secured by a remote controlled electric gate with video intercom system - and comes with the peace of mind of a 10 year Checkmate house warranty.Designed with modern day living in mind, all rooms have ultra low energy LED lighting, TV points and cat 5 data cabling, with selected power sockets having usb charging facilities. The ground floor and master bathroom enjoy underfloor heating whilst the hot water and heating is provided by highly efficient gas fired condensing boilers with zone controls. For your additional peace of mind the property has an alarm, pre wired for CCTV and has both security and ambient lighting within the grounds.With accommodation set over three levels and a flexible layout with options to create additional living space if desired, we recommend that you speak with the Cardwells team to arrange your private escorted viewing in order to fully appreciate all that is on offer. Please note that not all photographs are of this plot and are for illustrative purposes only.They say that first impressions count and when you and your guests first step into the hall and see the breathtakingly beautiful Oak Hardwood central staircase rising through the full height of the house, with galleried landings to each floor and Oak hardwood doors leading off, they will be seriously and rightfully impressed. The Kitchen is the heart of any home and this magnificent white open plan SieMatic kitchen with its Quooker instant hot water tap, Neff ovens, microwave, plate warmer, larder fridge, freezer, beautiful Corian work tops and polished stone floors, with underfloor heating, is certain to get yours racing. The large central island features a breakfast bar, storage and a five ring induction hob. This stunning and spacious L shaped room has a walk in larder and incorporates the kitchen, den and day dining areas with twin sets of bifold doors which both frame and allow uninterrupted access to the magnificent stone patio and landscaped garden beyond. The utility room leads off from the kitchen with sink, storage and is plumbed for a washing machine and dryer with access to the integral garage.The reception rooms are comfortably spacious and, as previously stated, the accommodation has been carefully designed to offer a degree of flexibility of layout to suit your individual preferences. Bedroom four on the first floor, for example, has been specifically laid out to offer the option of being used as a playroom or study. The garage is accessible from the hall as well as the utility room so that those preferring this space to be converted into an additional living room can enter from the main hall. The relaxing master bedroom suite offers the comfort and convenience of a large walk in wardrobe and luxurious 5 piece en suite featuring, amongst other essentials, his and hers sinks with marble floor and wall tiles. The remaining five bedrooms all have their own style and character design features, which are often lacking in new build properties. Some features are unique to each bedroom but may include vaulted ceilings, roof lights and Juliette balcony to create comfortable and interesting spaces in which to relax.The family bathroom, guest w.C and all five en suites have been beautifully designed and finished in Laufen and Vitra sanitaryware with porcelain tiles to the walls and floors. The showers have both drench and hand held shower heads which are fed by large, high pressure storage facilities ensuring that everyone can enjoy the most invigorating of showers.Having travelled through the imposing electric gate, the driveway provides plentiful parking and leads to the integral double garage with remote controlled electric door. To the rear is a magnificent stone patio extending to a lawned area with further landscaped garden beyond. We are informed that the plot extends to 0.25 acre.

Tenancy application/references


When a suitable property to rent has been found all persons aged eighteen or over will complete an Application Form and will be named in the Tenancy Agreement. We will take up references on behalf of our client, your landlord, which may include a bank reference for which your bank may charge a nominal fee, a credit reference, an employer's reference, an accountant¿s reference, and a previous landlord reference. A payment to indicate your commitment is required when you submit your application and is held against expenses and fees incurred. If your application is successful this payment will be deducted from your Initial Money. The payment is non-refundable should your application be unsuccessful or withdrawn in certain circumstances, the details of which are set out in the tinfo (Tenant Information Sheet). Please note that this payment in advance does not constitute a tenancy or offer of a tenancy but is proof of your serious intention to proceed.


Tenancy agreement

original Agreement and a further £100 for any extension Agreement(s) subsequently entered into. Once the Tenancy Agreement has been executed by you and the
landlord it is binding. Security deposit


Before your tenancy commences you will be required to pay a security deposit which will be a minimum of one month's rent. This deposit is held by us as stakeholders or passed to your landlord. listing.description: This outstanding grade II listed country house is thought to have origins dating back to the late 18th century and was the Rectory for Little Whelnetham Church from about 1832 until the early 20th century. Standing within 9 acres, Sicklesmere House retains a wealth of original features throughout including high ceilings, box sash windows, open fireplaces, ornate cornicing and heavy set wooden doors. The beautifully arranged accommodation is situated over three storeys and possesses a particularly elegant atmosphere with fine proportions, the country style kitchen, drawing room, dining room and orangery, being particularly outstanding rooms. The house is approached down a long private driveway and leads to the large range of outbuildings including an original coach house, stables and annexe accommodation. There are formal lawns (formally a tennis lawn), large pond, meadows and post and rail paddocks in about 9 acres (subject to survey) with a further 5.25 acres available subject to negotiation with the vendor.AccommodationUnique Gothic style entrance door opens to the reception hall (15'5" x 9'10" 4.7m x 3.0m). The entrance hall enjoys high ceilings and a great deal of light, creating a warm welcome with elegant staircase off to first floor. The drawing room (23'3" x 15'5" 7.1m x 4.7m) is a particularly elegant reception boasting beautiful proportions, looking out over the gardens with French doors opening to the lawn. An open fireplace with decorative marble surround sits centrally within the room and there is a large fitted cupboard with plenty of display shelves. The dining room (21'11" x 15'5" 6.7m x 4.7m) is a further grand reception room taking in views over the front and side gardens via two sets of box sash windows featuring original wooden shutters and an open brick fireplace with decorative wooden surround.The inner hallway has stairs rising to the first floor and doors leading to the outside and through to the morning room (20'0" x 12'5" 6.1m x 3.8m), a light room enjoying a south easterly aspect, fireplace with large wooden surround and wood burner inset. The study (14'9" x 10'5" 4.5m x 3.2m) is a large space with views and double doors opening to the outside of the property, fitted with an extensive range of built-in cupboards and book shelves. The kitchen/breakfast room (24'7" x 14'5" 7.5m x 4.4m) is a splendid room and is extensively fitted with a range of bespoke Smallbone wooden wall and base units beneath granite worktops with a Belfast sink inset, space for a double Rangemaster style oven, and integral dishwasher. The room offers ample space for a large dining table and there is a great deal of display shelves and a two hob aga inset a brick chimney breast. Character features include tiled flooring and exposed ceiling timbers. Double doors open to the boot room (12'1" x 10'9" 3.7m x 3.3m) which is a large room featuring chequered tiled flooring and door leading to the outside of the property with a natural well. There is plenty of storage space and enamel sink with space and plumbing for washing machine and tumble dryer. The cloakroom comprises a WC and wash basin. The orangery is a fantastic room complementing the house and enjoying triple aspect views. Double doors open to the gardens, and there are electric fittings for a hot tub outside the kitchen and orangery. The cellar (14'9" x 8'2" 4.5m x 2.5m) has brick steps leading through to a large dry storage area with original coal storage and two further large storage spaces creating an ideal space for wine racking., while a second room leads off the main cellar, which would have been the wine cellar.First FloorThe landing is a light and generous space and enjoys high ceilings and doors leading to the master bedroom (16'0" x 14'5" 4.9m x 4.4m) with outlook over the side and rear gardens and features two large built-in wardrobes one of which provides access through to the adjoining bedroom. There is also a separate dressing room further fitted with built-in wardrobes. The second bedroom (16'0" x 15'8" 4.9m x 4.8m) features views over the front aspect and a decorative fireplace with wooden surround and a built-in wardrobe. Bedroom three (16'0" x 12'5" 4.9m x 3.8m) is a light and airy room overlooking the rear gardens featuring a decorative fireplace with wooden surround and built-in wardrobes. The fourth bedroom (18'0" x 11'5" 5.5m x 3.5m) is a further spacious room with a decorative fireplace and an outlook over the side aspect. The shower room (12'5" x 3'11" 3.8m x 1.2m) comprises WC, wash basin and shower cubicle. Bedroom five (15'8" x 11'9" 4.8m x 3.6m) is a further spacious room overlooking the rear gardens and grounds. The family bathroom (12'1" x 11'5" 3.7m x 3.5m) is a large room fitted with an airing cupboard and comprises WC, wash basin and panelled bath with Victorian style shower attachment over. There is a large storage cupboard which could be converted into a shower room, and potential for two Jack and Jill en-suites to serve four of the bedrooms.Second FloorThe landing is separated into two areas and featuring eaves storage space. This outstanding grade II listed country house is thought to have origins dating back to the late 18th century and was the Rectory for Little Whelnetham Church from about 1832 until the early 20th century. Standing within 9 acres, Sicklesmere House retains a wealth of original features throughout including high ceilings, box sash windows, open fireplaces, ornate cornicing and heavy set wooden doors. The beautifully arranged accommodation is situated over three storeys and possesses a particularly elegant atmosphere with fine proportions, the country style kitchen, drawing room, dining room and orangery, being particularly outstanding rooms. The house is approached down a long private driveway and leads to the large range of outbuildings including an original coach house, stables and annexe accommodation. There are formal lawns (formally a tennis lawn), large pond, meadows and post and rail paddocks in about 9 acres (subject to survey) with a further 5.25 acres available subject to negotiation with the vendor.
